<title>BELGIUM: EU urges greater eastern efforts on capital moves.</title>
<headline>EU urges greater eastern efforts on capital moves.</headline>
<dateline>BRUSSELS 1997-07-08</dateline>
<text>
<p>The European Union has urged 10 eastern European applicant countries to press on with reforms in liberalising capital movements and their banking sectors.</p>
<p>Conclusions issued by the Luxembourg EU presidency after EU finance ministers met with their eastern European colleagues on Monday said although progress on capital liberalisation had been positive, the performance was different from country to country and further efforts were needed.</p>
<p>&quot;The experience from capital liberalisation has been positive as the relaxation of restrictions on the movement of capital was operated in an orderly manner, without serious balance of payment difficulties,&quot; the conclusions said.</p>
<p>&quot;However the opening of the capital account entails risks of destabilising capital flows if market expectations are reversed,&quot; it said.</p>
<p>Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Slovenia, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Bulgaria and Romania all attended the meeting.</p>
<p>&quot;Experience shows that coherent and sustainable economic and financial policies and implementation of the necessary structural reforms is the best way to limit the risks of destabilising capital flows as restrictions on the movement of capital are relaxed,&quot; the conclusions said.</p>
<p>The paper also said that as regards the banking sector &quot; progress has to be consolidated and deepened as the situation remains still fragile.&quot;</p>
<p>-- Brussels newsroom 32 2 287 68 37</p>
